    { id: "fb236", title: "Grief Literacy", text: "Grief literacy is the capacity to understand and respond ___1___ bereavement \u2014 in ourselves and in others. Many people feel uncomfortable around grief, unsure of ___2___ to say or do. This discomfort often leads to avoidance at the very moment support is most needed.\n\nCommon phrases intended to comfort can cause harm. Telling someone that a loved one is ___3___ a better place or that time heals all wounds may dismiss their pain. Simply being present and acknowledging the loss is ___4___ more helpful.\n\nWorkplaces are beginning to address grief more thoughtfully. Standard bereavement leave of three to five days is widely regarded ___5___ inadequate. Progressive employers offer extended leave, phased returns, and access to counselling. ___6___ communities become more grief-literate, the isolation that often accompanies loss will diminish. Death is universal, ___7___ our preparedness for it need not ___8___ so poor. Teaching children about loss in age-appropriate ways builds resilience ___9___ serves them throughout ___10___.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "to", alt: [] }, { id: 2, answer: "what", alt: [] }, { id: 3, answer: "in", alt: ["at"] }, { id: 4, answer: "far", alt: ["much"] }, { id: 5, answer: "as", alt: [] }, { id: 6, answer: "As", alt: ["When", "Once"] }, { id: 7, answer: "yet", alt: ["but"] }, { id: 8, answer: "be", alt: ["remain"] }, { id: 9, answer: "that", alt: ["and", "which"] }, { id: 10, answer: "life", alt: ["adulthood"] }] },
    { id: "fb237", title: "Vertical Forests", text: "Vertical forests are high-rise buildings covered ___1___ trees and shrubs on every balcony. The concept, pioneered by Italian architect Stefano Boeri, creates a living ecosystem within an urban tower. Each building hosts ___2___ equivalent of hectares of forest.\n\nThe vegetation provides natural insulation, reducing energy consumption ___3___ heating and cooling. Trees absorb carbon dioxide and filter fine dust particles from the air. Biodiversity increases as birds and insects find habitat ___4___ the heart of the city.\n\nMaintenance is a genuine challenge. Trees at great heights face extreme wind and require ___5___ watering systems. Structural engineering must account ___6___ the weight of soil and mature plants. These complexities add to construction costs, ___7___ proponents argue the long-term environmental returns justify the investment. Similar projects are now ___8___ way in China, Switzerland, and the Netherlands. ___9___ the model can be scaled affordably, vertical forests could redefine ___10___ relationship between nature and urban architecture.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "in", alt: ["with"] }, { id: 2, answer: "the", alt: ["an"] }, { id: 3, answer: "for", alt: ["on"] }, { id: 4, answer: "in", alt: ["at"] }, { id: 5, answer: "specialised", alt: ["automated", "dedicated"] }, { id: 6, answer: "for", alt: [] }, { id: 7, answer: "but", alt: ["yet"] }, { id: 8, answer: "under", alt: ["on the"] }, { id: 9, answer: "If", alt: ["Should", "Once"] }, { id: 10, answer: "the", alt: ["our"] }] },
    { id: "fb238", title: "Sleep Tourism", text: "Sleep tourism is a growing niche in the travel industry. Hotels are designing rooms specifically ___1___ optimise rest, with blackout curtains, temperature regulation, and sound insulation. Some offer sleep concierge services and personalised pillow ___2___.\n\nThe trend reflects a broader cultural shift. People are beginning to value sleep ___3___ a form of wellness rather than a sign of laziness. High-end retreats offer programmes combining sleep science, meditation, and nutrition.\n\nThere is irony in travelling to sleep better. ___4___, the unfamiliar environment of a hotel often disrupts rest. Jet lag compounds the problem ___5___ long-haul travellers. ___6___, sleep-focused hotels address these issues with evidence-based design. Circadian lighting systems adjust ___7___ the time of day. Mattress firmness and room temperature can be customised. ___8___ the concept seems indulgent, it highlights a serious truth: millions ___9___ people are chronically sleep-deprived. If a hotel stay inspires better habits at home, the investment may well be ___10___ it.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "to", alt: [] }, { id: 2, answer: "menus", alt: ["selections", "options"] }, { id: 3, answer: "as", alt: [] }, { id: 4, answer: "After all", alt: ["Indeed"] }, { id: 5, answer: "for", alt: ["among"] }, { id: 6, answer: "However", alt: ["Yet", "Nevertheless"] }, { id: 7, answer: "to", alt: ["with"] }, { id: 8, answer: "While", alt: ["Although", "Though"] }, { id: 9, answer: "of", alt: [] }, { id: 10, answer: "worth", alt: [] }] },
    { id: "fb239", title: "Conflict Minerals", text: "Conflict minerals are natural resources extracted in war zones and sold ___1___ finance armed groups. Tin, tungsten, tantalum, and gold are the most commonly cited. They are found in everyday electronics, ___2___ smartphones to laptops.\n\nThe human cost is devastating. Miners, including children, work in dangerous conditions ___3___ minimal pay. Armed groups control mines through violence and intimidation. Profits fund ongoing ___4___ that have displaced millions.\n\nLegislation now requires companies to trace their supply chains. The EU and the US have introduced due ___5___ rules for importers. ___6___, enforcement is uneven and loopholes persist. Some companies have responded by avoiding the affected regions entirely, which ___7___ harms legitimate miners. A more nuanced approach supports responsible sourcing ___8___ punishing conflict-free operations. Consumer awareness is growing, ___9___ few people check the origins of the metals in their devices. Genuine progress requires sustained pressure from governments, businesses, and consumers ___10___.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "to", alt: ["and"] }, { id: 2, answer: "from", alt: [] }, { id: 3, answer: "for", alt: ["with"] }, { id: 4, answer: "conflict", alt: ["violence", "warfare"] }, { id: 5, answer: "diligence", alt: ["care"] }, { id: 6, answer: "However", alt: ["Yet", "Nevertheless"] }, { id: 7, answer: "ironically", alt: ["paradoxically"] }, { id: 8, answer: "without", alt: ["rather than"] }, { id: 9, answer: "yet", alt: ["but"] }, { id: 10, answer: "alike", alt: ["together"] }] },
    { id: "fb240", title: "Tactile Literacy", text: "Braille remains essential for literacy ___1___ blind and visually impaired people. Despite the rise of screen readers and audiobooks, the ability to read ___2___ touch provides cognitive benefits that listening cannot replicate. Braille readers tend to be better spellers and more confident writers.\n\nBraille literacy rates have declined ___3___ recent decades. Only a fraction of visually impaired children learn to read Braille, partly because specialist teachers are ___4___ short supply. Digital devices have shifted emphasis toward audio solutions.\n\nAdvocates argue this trend is ___5___. Reading by touch engages the brain differently from listening. It promotes independence in ways ___6___ audio alone cannot. Labelling in Braille on public signage, medicine, and consumer products remains inconsistent. ___7___ technology has expanded options, it should complement rather than replace tactile ___8___. The challenge is ensuring that blind individuals have the ___9___ to choose how they access information, rather than having that choice made ___10___ them.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "among", alt: ["for", "amongst"] }, { id: 2, answer: "by", alt: ["through", "via"] }, { id: 3, answer: "in", alt: ["over"] }, { id: 4, answer: "in", alt: [] }, { id: 5, answer: "harmful", alt: ["damaging", "concerning"] }, { id: 6, answer: "that", alt: ["which"] }, { id: 7, answer: "While", alt: ["Although", "Though"] }, { id: 8, answer: "literacy", alt: ["reading"] }, { id: 9, answer: "freedom", alt: ["right", "ability"] }, { id: 10, answer: "for", alt: ["about"] }] },
    { id: "fb241", title: "Phantom Traffic Jams", text: "Phantom traffic jams form without any obvious cause. A single driver braking slightly ___1___ trigger a chain reaction that ripples backward through traffic for miles. The phenomenon has been modelled ___2___ and confirmed by real-world experiments.\n\nThe wave travels in the opposite direction ___3___ traffic flow. Drivers further back experience worse delays than those ___4___ triggered the disturbance. By the time they reach the original point, the road ahead is completely clear.\n\nAdaptive cruise control could help break ___5___ cycle. Automated systems maintain consistent spacing, damping the waves before they amplify. Simulations suggest that ___6___ a small proportion of vehicles using such technology could eliminate phantom jams ___7___. ___8___ fully autonomous vehicles arrive, connected car networks will communicate to smooth traffic flow further. ___9___ then, simply maintaining a steady speed and leaving adequate gaps can make a genuine ___10___ for every driver on the road.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "can", alt: ["may"] }, { id: 2, answer: "mathematically", alt: ["computationally"] }, { id: 3, answer: "to", alt: ["from"] }, { id: 4, answer: "who", alt: ["that"] }, { id: 5, answer: "the", alt: ["this"] }, { id: 6, answer: "even", alt: ["just"] }, { id: 7, answer: "entirely", alt: ["completely", "altogether"] }, { id: 8, answer: "When", alt: ["Once", "As"] }, { id: 9, answer: "Until", alt: ["Before"] }, { id: 10, answer: "difference", alt: ["impact"] }] },
    { id: "fb242", title: "Emotional Support Animals", text: "Emotional support animals provide comfort to people ___1___ mental health conditions. Unlike service animals, they are not trained to perform specific tasks. Their presence alone offers therapeutic benefits ___2___ reduce anxiety and depression.\n\nThe legal status of emotional support animals varies ___3___. In some countries, they are recognised in housing law but not in public access regulations. Airlines have tightened their ___4___ after incidents involving unusual animals on flights.\n\nThe system is vulnerable to abuse. Online services sell certification letters with minimal ___5___. This undermines the legitimacy of people who genuinely benefit ___6___ emotional support animals. ___7___ a result, some landlords and businesses have become sceptical of all claims.\n\nClearer regulations would protect both people and animals. Standardised assessments could verify genuine need ___8___ preventing fraud. The therapeutic bond between humans and animals is well documented \u2014 what is needed is a framework ___9___ honours it ___10___ allowing exploitation.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "with", alt: ["experiencing"] }, { id: 2, answer: "that", alt: ["which"] }, { id: 3, answer: "widely", alt: ["considerably", "greatly"] }, { id: 4, answer: "policies", alt: ["rules", "restrictions"] }, { id: 5, answer: "verification", alt: ["scrutiny", "oversight"] }, { id: 6, answer: "from", alt: [] }, { id: 7, answer: "As", alt: [] }, { id: 8, answer: "while", alt: ["whilst", "and"] }, { id: 9, answer: "that", alt: ["which"] }, { id: 10, answer: "without", alt: ["while not"] }] },
    { id: "fb243", title: "Citizen Journalism", text: "Citizen journalism has transformed how news is gathered and shared. Ordinary people ___1___ smartphones can document events as they unfold. Their footage often reaches audiences before professional reporters ___2___ on the scene.\n\nThe Arab Spring demonstrated the power of citizen reporting. Activists broadcast protests ___3___ the world despite government media blackouts. Social media turned local events ___4___ international news within minutes.\n\nQuality and accuracy remain serious concerns. Citizen journalists lack the training and editorial oversight ___5___ professional newsrooms provide. Misinformation can spread rapidly when unverified content goes ___6___. Context is often missing, leading viewers to draw incomplete conclusions. ___7___, the best citizen journalism fills gaps that mainstream media overlooks. Community reporters cover stories ___8___ larger outlets ignore. The challenge is developing systems that harness citizen contributions ___9___ maintaining standards of accuracy. When professional and citizen journalism work ___10___ concert, the public is better informed.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "with", alt: ["carrying"] }, { id: 2, answer: "arrive", alt: ["are"] }, { id: 3, answer: "to", alt: ["around"] }, { id: 4, answer: "into", alt: ["to"] }, { id: 5, answer: "that", alt: ["which"] }, { id: 6, answer: "viral", alt: ["unchecked"] }, { id: 7, answer: "Nevertheless", alt: ["However", "Still"] }, { id: 8, answer: "that", alt: ["which"] }, { id: 9, answer: "while", alt: ["whilst", "and"] }, { id: 10, answer: "in", alt: [] }] },
    { id: "fb244", title: "Ocean Thermal Energy", text: "Ocean thermal energy conversion exploits the temperature difference ___1___ warm surface water and cold deep water. In tropical regions, this difference can exceed twenty degrees. The gradient is sufficient ___2___ drive a heat engine and generate electricity.\n\nThe technology has been understood ___3___ over a century but has never achieved commercial viability. Plant construction costs are enormous, and the energy output per unit ___4___ modest compared to other renewables.\n\nRecent advances in materials and engineering have revived ___5___. Small-scale plants are operating in Japan and Hawaii. Island nations with limited land ___6___ abundant ocean resources find the technology particularly appealing. Beyond electricity, the cold deep water has applications in air conditioning, aquaculture, and freshwater ___7___. ___8___ the challenges of scale and cost are overcome, ocean thermal energy could provide baseload power ___9___ tropical regions worldwide. Its constancy gives it an advantage ___10___ intermittent sources like wind and solar.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "between", alt: ["among"] }, { id: 2, answer: "to", alt: [] }, { id: 3, answer: "for", alt: [] }, { id: 4, answer: "is", alt: ["remains"] }, { id: 5, answer: "interest", alt: ["hope", "attention"] }, { id: 6, answer: "but", alt: ["yet"] }, { id: 7, answer: "production", alt: ["generation", "desalination"] }, { id: 8, answer: "If", alt: ["Once", "Should"] }, { id: 9, answer: "to", alt: ["for", "in"] }, { id: 10, answer: "over", alt: ["above"] }] },
    { id: "fb245", title: "Play in Adulthood", text: "Play is often dismissed ___1___ a childhood activity, yet it serves vital functions throughout life. Adults who engage in playful activities report higher creativity, stronger relationships, and better stress management. The absence of play ___2___ impoverish adult life.\n\nNeuroscience supports these claims. Play activates reward centres ___3___ the brain and stimulates neural connections. It promotes cognitive flexibility \u2014 the ability to shift ___4___ different ideas and perspectives. These benefits do not diminish with age.\n\nModern culture tends to equate adulthood ___5___ seriousness. Free time is filled with productivity rather ___6___ exploration. This leaves little room for unstructured, spontaneous activity. Workplaces that encourage playfulness \u2014 ___7___ creative brainstorming sessions or informal social events \u2014 often see improved team dynamics. The key is redefining play not as the opposite ___8___ work but as its complement. ___9___ adults give themselves permission to play, they frequently discover a vitality they did not realise they ___10___ missing.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "as", alt: ["like"] }, { id: 2, answer: "can", alt: ["may"] }, { id: 3, answer: "in", alt: ["within"] }, { id: 4, answer: "between", alt: ["among"] }, { id: 5, answer: "with", alt: ["and"] }, { id: 6, answer: "than", alt: [] }, { id: 7, answer: "through", alt: ["via"] }, { id: 8, answer: "of", alt: [] }, { id: 9, answer: "When", alt: ["Once", "If"] }, { id: 10, answer: "were", alt: ["had been"] }] },
    { id: "fb246", title: "Dark Tourism", text: "Dark tourism involves visiting sites associated ___1___ death, tragedy, or suffering. Concentration camps, battlefields, and disaster zones attract millions of visitors annually. The phenomenon raises complex ethical questions about remembrance and ___2___.\n\nProponents argue that such visits promote education and empathy. Standing ___3___ a place of historical tragedy creates an emotional connection that textbooks cannot. Memorial sites honour victims and ensure their stories are ___4___ forgotten.\n\nCritics worry about commodification. When tragedy becomes a tourist attraction, ___5___ is a risk of trivialising suffering. Selfies at memorial sites have sparked widespread ___6___. The behaviour of visitors matters as much as their motivation ___7___ visiting.\n\nSite management plays a crucial role. Thoughtful interpretation, respectful design, and clear codes of ___8___ help maintain dignity. ___9___ dark tourism is approached with sensitivity, it can serve as a powerful tool for collective memory. The discomfort it provokes is ___10___ the point.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "with", alt: ["alongside"] }, { id: 2, answer: "exploitation", alt: ["entertainment", "voyeurism"] }, { id: 3, answer: "in", alt: ["at"] }, { id: 4, answer: "not", alt: ["never"] }, { id: 5, answer: "there", alt: [] }, { id: 6, answer: "debate", alt: ["controversy", "outrage"] }, { id: 7, answer: "for", alt: ["in"] }, { id: 8, answer: "conduct", alt: ["behaviour"] }, { id: 9, answer: "When", alt: ["If", "Where"] }, { id: 10, answer: "precisely", alt: ["exactly"] }] },
    { id: "fb247", title: "Rewearable Fashion Tech", text: "Wearable technology is merging ___1___ fashion in unexpected ways. Smart fabrics can monitor heart rate, track movement, and ___2___ regulate body temperature. The line between clothing and device is blurring.\n\nEarly wearable tech was bulky and unattractive. Modern designs are virtually indistinguishable ___3___ conventional garments. Conductive fibres woven into fabric eliminate the need for separate sensors. Washing and durability have improved ___4___.\n\nApplications extend beyond fitness tracking. Workers ___5___ hazardous environments can wear garments that detect toxic gases. Elderly people benefit from clothing that monitors vital signs and alerts carers ___6___ abnormalities. Athletes gain real-time performance data without cumbersome equipment.\n\nPrivacy concerns accompany any technology that collects bodily data. Questions about ___7___ owns the information and how it is stored remain ___8___. ___9___ the technology matures, clear regulations must keep pace. The potential to improve health outcomes is significant, ___10___ only if trust is established.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "with", alt: ["and"] }, { id: 2, answer: "even", alt: ["also"] }, { id: 3, answer: "from", alt: [] }, { id: 4, answer: "significantly", alt: ["considerably", "dramatically"] }, { id: 5, answer: "in", alt: ["within"] }, { id: 6, answer: "to", alt: ["about"] }, { id: 7, answer: "who", alt: ["what body"] }, { id: 8, answer: "unresolved", alt: ["unanswered", "open"] }, { id: 9, answer: "As", alt: ["While"] }, { id: 10, answer: "but", alt: ["yet"] }] },
    { id: "fb248", title: "Bibliotherapy", text: "Bibliotherapy uses reading as a therapeutic tool. Books are prescribed ___1___ help patients explore their emotions, gain perspective, and develop coping strategies. The practice has roots stretching ___2___ to ancient Greece.\n\nSelf-help books are the most obvious form, but fiction plays an equally important ___3___. Reading about characters facing similar struggles creates a sense of shared experience. This recognition \u2014 that one is ___4___ alone \u2014 can be profoundly comforting.\n\nClinical trials have shown measurable results. Patients prescribed specific reading programmes report reduced symptoms ___5___ anxiety and depression. In some cases, bibliotherapy proves as effective ___6___ traditional cognitive behavioural therapy. Libraries have partnered ___7___ health services to make prescribed books freely available. Children's bibliotherapy uses picture books to help young people process difficult emotions ___8___ as grief, bullying, and family change. ___9___ reading cannot solve every problem, it offers a gentle, accessible, and deeply human form of ___10___.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "to", alt: [] }, { id: 2, answer: "back", alt: ["again"] }, { id: 3, answer: "role", alt: ["part"] }, { id: 4, answer: "not", alt: ["never"] }, { id: 5, answer: "of", alt: ["from"] }, { id: 6, answer: "as", alt: [] }, { id: 7, answer: "with", alt: ["alongside"] }, { id: 8, answer: "such", alt: ["like"] }, { id: 9, answer: "While", alt: ["Although", "Though"] }, { id: 10, answer: "support", alt: ["healing", "therapy"] }] },
    { id: "fb249", title: "Traffic Calming", text: "Traffic calming measures reduce vehicle speeds ___1___ residential streets. Speed bumps, chicanes, and raised crossings force drivers to slow down. The goal is to create safer environments for pedestrians and ___2___.\n\nEvidence strongly supports their effectiveness. Streets with calming measures see ___3___ to sixty percent fewer serious accidents. Lower speeds give drivers more time ___4___ react and reduce the severity of any collisions that occur.\n\nResidents generally welcome the changes, ___5___ some complain about increased travel time. Emergency services occasionally raise concerns about delayed response. Careful design can address ___6___ objections \u2014 speed cushions, for instance, allow wider vehicles to pass without significant delay.\n\nThe broader trend is ___7___ rethinking streets as shared spaces rather than vehicle corridors. Cities that prioritise people ___8___ cars tend to be safer, healthier, and more economically vibrant. ___9___ small reduction in speed can be the difference between life and death ___10___ a pedestrian is struck.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "on", alt: ["in", "along"] }, { id: 2, answer: "cyclists", alt: ["residents"] }, { id: 3, answer: "up", alt: [] }, { id: 4, answer: "to", alt: [] }, { id: 5, answer: "though", alt: ["although", "while"] }, { id: 6, answer: "both", alt: ["these"] }, { id: 7, answer: "toward", alt: ["towards", "about"] }, { id: 8, answer: "over", alt: ["above"] }, { id: 9, answer: "A", alt: ["Even a"] }, { id: 10, answer: "when", alt: ["if", "should"] }] },
    { id: "fb250", title: "Conscious Consumerism", text: "Ethical consumerism involves making purchasing decisions ___1___ on moral values. Shoppers consider the environmental impact, labour conditions, and corporate practices behind ___2___ they buy. The movement has grown from a niche concern into a mainstream force.\n\nFair trade certification was among the first tools ___3___ guide ethical purchases. It guarantees minimum prices for producers and prohibits exploitative labour. Organic labels, cruelty-free logos, and carbon-neutral certifications have ___4___ followed.\n\nSkeptics argue that ethical shopping places too much burden ___5___ individuals. Systemic change through regulation, they claim, is more effective than personal choice. Others point out that consumer demand ___6___ drives corporate behaviour. When enough people ___7___ for ethically produced goods, companies respond.\n\nThe reality likely requires ___8___. Individual action and structural reform are not mutually exclusive \u2014 they reinforce each ___9___. Every purchase is a small vote for the kind of world we want. ___10___ these votes alone cannot transform the system, they send a signal that is increasingly hard to ignore.", blanks: [{ id: 1, answer: "based", alt: ["grounded"] }, { id: 2, answer: "what", alt: [] }, { id: 3, answer: "to", alt: ["that"] }, { id: 4, answer: "since", alt: ["subsequently"] }, { id: 5, answer: "on", alt: ["upon"] }, { id: 6, answer: "ultimately", alt: ["directly"] }, { id: 7, answer: "ask", alt: ["call", "push"] }, { id: 8, answer: "both", alt: ["each"] }, { id: 9, answer: "other", alt: [] }, { id: 10, answer: "While", alt: ["Although", "Though"] }] }
